
## DEMO

The iSCSI is installed on VM named **server**. Connect to it and and check its iSCSI configuration.

```bash
# SSH to the server VM via the utility server
ssh 192.168.51.40 -J utility

# Check its IP address, which is 192.168.51.40/24
ip a s
```

### Check the list of iSCSI targets


```bash
# SSH to the server
targetcli
```

```bash
ls
```

```bash
...
# There is
# iSCSI target set up named iqn.2021-10.com.example:server.disk1
# Trusted Portal Group named tpg1
# The ACL allows access for an initiator system named iqn.2021-10.com.example:client-server.disk1
# To use a LUN named lun0
# And all this is available on the IP:Port 192.168.51.40:3260
...
```

### Create the PV

cat > pv.yaml

```bash
apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolume
metadata:
  name: iscsi-pv
spec:
  capacity:
    storage: 1Gi
  volumeMode: Block
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
  claimRef:
    namespace: web-demo
    name: web-logs
  persistentVolumeReclaimPolicy: Retain
  iscsi:
    targetPortal: 192.168.51.40:3260
    iqn: iqn.2021-10.com.example:server.disk1
    lun: 0
    initiatorName: iqn.2021-10.com.example:client-server.disk1
    # fsType: ext4
    # readOnly: false
```

```bash
oc get pv
```

### ### Create the PVC

Create a PVC named `web-logs` to bind to this PV

```bash
apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolumeClaim
metadata:
  name: web-logs
  namespace: web-demo
spec:
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
  storageClassName: ""
  volumeMode: Block
  resources:
    requests:
      storage: 1Gi
  volumeName: iscsi-pv
```

Check that the pvc is bound

```bash
oc get pvc
```

```bash
oc new-project web-demo
```

```bash
virtctl create vm \
  --name=db \
  --instancetype=u1.small \
  --preference=rhel.10 \
  --volume-datasource=src:openshift-virtualization-os-images/rhel10-mariadb \
  --namespace web-demo \
  --cloud-init-user-data "$(cat cloud-config.b64)"
```

From the OpenShift Web Console, add a disk of type `Volume` to the `web` VM, from the PVC named `web-logs`.

Connect to the VM console and check that the disk has been added to the VM.

```bash
lsblk -fp
```
```bash
...
/dev/sda
...
```

Format the disk and mount it

```bash
mkfs.ext4 /dev/sda
```

```bash
# Creat a mounting to store the httpd log files
mkdir -pv /var/log/httpd

# Mount /dev/sda to /var/log/httpd
mount  /dev/sda /var/log/httpd
```
